UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199687900626
AB  - This paper models a large importer of a competitively produced good for which there are nonlinear adjustment costs in production. If producers have rational expectations and the importer is unable to make a credible commitment regarding future tariffs, market power may be disadvantageous. This is more likely to occur when the difference between short- and long-run elasticities of supply are large. This result depends on the particular subgame perfect equilibrium that is chosen. If producers were capable of strategic behavior, other equilibria, which rely on trigger strategies, would be reasonable and market power could no longer be disadvantageous.
