UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199687900523
AB  - Previous literature on the use of trade policy for insurance has relied implicitly on moral hazard and adverse selection as the reasons for the failure of private markets for risk-bearing. This paper begins with the observation that such forces should be incorporated explicitly into the models to ensure a fair comparison between markets and governments. For the case of moral hazard, it is found that market equilibrium given exclusive insurance is an informationally constrained Pareto optimum. In one case of non-exclusive insurance, a systematic role for government insurance is found, but the scope of trade policy is ambiguous.
